  <text>
     <!-- 
        The ideal way to create a quotation id for references that don't have standard breakdown such bible quotes or "auctoritates" or sentences commentaries is to include the relevant reference info in descending order, using the corresponding author and work id.
        So for Augustine a good id is Augustine_deTrinitate_14_1_a   
        
        While lengthy, this would make future string scrapping easier. If a quote id got detached from its associated information, it could still be identified by its id.
        
        In the future "work title" should probably be constructed in the same way, again excluding bible quotes another genres that have a more intuitive system
        
        Ideally, name and title id should be in Latin. 
        They should be short, but long enough to be unique. 
        Aquinas or Bonavenure is sufficient, but Giles or Gregory is not, 
        last names are preferred, but, for example in the case of Giles of Rome, Rome is not sufficient so AegidiusRomanus is preferred. 
        Camelback syntax is preferred
     
     -->
     
     
     
      <body>
         <list>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_22_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Secundum mensuram peccati oportet esse satisfactionem</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">20</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_24_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Hanc beatitudinem nulli dari debere nisi illi, cui penitus dimissa sunt peccata, nec hanc dimissionem fieri nisi debito reddito, quod debetur pro peccato secundum magnitudinem peccati, supra positis rationibus puto me sufficienter ostendisse</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">24</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_21_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Cum considero actionem ipsam, levissimum quiddam video esse; sed cum intueor quid sit contra voluntatem dei, gravissimum quiddam et nulli damno comparabile intelligo</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">21</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <!-- i don't think this chapter designation is right; it might be part of an older system. -->
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_2_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">ita qui honorem alicuius violat, non sufficit honorem reddere, si non secundum exhonorationis factam molestiam aliquid, quod placeat illi quem exhonoravit, restituat</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">2</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_20_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Cum reddis aliquid quod debes deo, etiam si non peccasti, non debes hoc computare pro debito quod debes pro peccato. Omnia autem ista debes deo quae dicis.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">20</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_35_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Quapropter sicut me rationabiliter deduxisti ad hoc, ut videam peccatorem hominem hoc debere deo pro peccato quod et reddere nequit, et nisi reddiderit salvari non valet.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">35</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_24_b">
               <quote type="Scholastic">A: Si homo dicitur iniustus, qui homini non reddit quod debet: multo magis iniustus est, qui deo quod debet non reddit. B: Si potest et non reddit, vere iniustus est. Si vero non potest: quomodo iniustus est? A: Forsitan si nulla est in illo causa impotentiae, aliquatenus excusari potest. Sed si in ipsa impotentia culpa est: sicut non levigat peccatum, ita non excusat non reddentem debitum.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">24</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_11_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">et haec est satisfactio, quam omnis peccator deo debet facere.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">11</biblScope>
               </bibl>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_DeConcordia_3_13_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">In beatitudine autem, secundum omnium sensum, est sufficientia competentium commodorum sine omni indigentia</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_DeConcordia">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Augustine</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_DeConcordia">De concordia</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">3</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">13</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation"/>
               <note type="firstIdentification"></note>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_2_14_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Si omne bonum tam bonum est quam mala est eius destructio.‚Äù</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">CurDeusHomo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">2</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">14</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation">F.S. Schmitt.  Romae, 1940, II, 114, lin. 22</note>
               <note type="firstIdentification">Wodeham, Ordinatio, prologue q. 1</note>
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_1_1_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Sicut rectus ordo exigit ut profunda Christianae fidei prius credamus, quam ea praesumamus ratione discutere, ita negligentia mihi videtur, si, postquam confirmati sumus in fide, non studemus quod credimus intelligere.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">CurDeusHomo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">1</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">1</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation">Anselmus, Cur Deus Homo, I, c. 1</note>
               <note type="firstIdentification">Gracilis Book 1, q. 1</note> <!-- gracilis reports this as fall in book 1, c. 2, but in modern editions it is chapter 1 --> 
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_CurDeusHomo_2_17_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Omnis quippe necessitas et impossibilitas eius subiacet voluntati; illius autem voluntas nulli subditur necessitati aut impossibilitati.</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Anselm_CurDeusHomo">Cur Deus Homo</title>
                  <biblScope type="librum">2</biblScope>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">17</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation">Anselmus, Cur Deus Homo, II, c. 17</note> <!-- gracilis, substitutes 'possibilitas' for 'necessitas'; quote also used by Bradwardine in De Causa Dei, see reprint 1964, 209 C; 647D -->
               <note type="firstIdentification">Gracilis, Book 1, q. 27</note>  
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_DeProcessioneSpiritusSancti_7_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">omnia sunt idem ubi non obviat</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_CurDeusHomo">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#DeProcessioneSpiritusSancti">De processione Spiritus Sancti</title>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">7</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation">Anselmus, De processione Spiritus Sancti, c. 7 <!-- unsure Marsilus of Inghen, q. 22, p. 31n26 --></note> 
               <note type="firstIdentification">Gracilis, Book 1, q. 23</note>  
            </item>
            <item xml:id="Anselm_Monologion_48_a">
               <quote type="Scholastic">Rem etenim cogitare cuius memoriam habemus, hoc est mente eam dicere, verbum vero rei est ipsa est ipsa cogitatio ad eius similitudinem ex memoria formata</quote>
               <bibl type="Anselm_Monologion">
                  <author ref="#Anselm">Anselm</author>
                  <title ref="#Monologion">De processione Spiritus Sancti</title>
                  <biblScope type="capitulus">48</biblScope>
               </bibl>
               <note type="citation">Anselmus, Monologion, c. 48</note> 
               <note type="firstIdentification">Gracilis, Book 1, q. 24</note>  
            </item>
            
         </list>
